"accepted_answer":false,"topic_accepted_answer":null,"can_vote":false},{"id":3419842,"name":"Gavin Matthews","username":"bovlb","avatar_template":"/user_avatar/www.chiefdelphi.com/bovlb/{size}/167232_2.png","created_at":"2024-08-31T23:03:25.244Z","cooked":"<p>This code has a nice separation of concerns between different levels.</p>
<p>I got stuck on one specific part:</p>
<aside class="quote no-group quote-modified" data-username="narmstro" data-post="1" data-topic="470539">
<div class="title">
<div class="quote-controls"></div>
<img loading="lazy" alt="" width="24" height="24" src="https://www.chiefdelphi.com/letter_avatar_proxy/v4/letter/n/5e9695/48.png" class="avatar"> narmstro:</div>
<blockquote>
<pre data-code-wrap="java"><code class="lang-java">MutableMeasure&lt;Voltage&gt; sysIdAppliedVoltageMeasure = 
    MutableMeasure.mutable(Volts.of(0.0));
...
.voltage(
        sysIdAppliedVoltageMeasure
                .mut_replace(appliedVoltage.getAsDouble(), 
                    Volts))
</code></pre>
</blockquote>
</aside>
<p>because I started wondering if there could be a better way to tie a MutableMeasure to a DoubleSupplier.  I threw together <a href="https://gist.github.com/bovlb/ee9b9eaf8f7dbccea2be7ffc0352c15b" rel="noopener nofollow ugc">an untested gist for MutableMeasureSupplier</a>, but the resulting code is only slightly simpler:</p>
<pre data-code-wrap="java"><code class="lang-java">MutableMeasureSupplier&lt;Voltage&gt; sysIdAppliedVoltageMeasure = 
    new MutableMeasureSupplier&lt;Units.Volts&gt;(appliedVoltage);
...
.voltage(sysIdAppliedVoltageMeasure.get())
</code></pre>","post_number":2,"post_type":1,"posts_count":11,"updated_at":"2024-08-31T23:03:25.244Z","reply_count":0,"reply_to_post_number":null,"quote_count":1,"incoming_link_count":0,"reads":101,"readers_count":100,"score":35.2,"yours":false,"topic_id":470539,"topic_slug":"shootersubsystem-design-feedback","display_username":"Gavin Matthews","primary_group_name":null,"flair_name":null,"flair_url":null,"flair_bg_color":null,"flair_color":null,"flair_group_id":null,"badges_granted":[],"version":1,"can_edit":false,"can_delete":false,"can_recover":false,"can_see_hidden_post":true,"can_wiki":false,"link_counts":[{"url":"https://gist.github.com/bovlb/ee9b9eaf8f7dbccea2be7ffc0352c15b","internal":false,"reflection":false,"title":"mutable measure from double supplier · GitHub","clicks":4}],"read":true,"user_title":"","bookmarked":false,"actions_summary":[{"id":2,"count":1}],"moderator":false,"admin":false,"staff":false,"user_id":38743,"hidden":false,"trust_level":2,"deleted_at":null,"user_deleted":false,"edit_reason":null,"can_view_edit_history":true,"wiki":false,"user_custom_fields":{"user_field_4":"Programming mentor, Team 2102, RI, CSA (he/him)"},"post_url":"/t/shootersubsystem-design-feedback/470539/2","custom_user_title":"Programming mentor, Team 2102, RI, CSA (he/him)","reactions":[{"id":"heart","type":"emoji","count":1}],"current_user_reaction":null,"reaction_users_count":1,"current_user_used_main_reaction":false,"can_accept_answer":false,"can_unaccept_answer":false,"accepted_answer":false,"topic_accepted_answer":null},{"id":3420009,"name":"Gavin Matthews","username":"bovlb","avatar_template":"/user_avatar/www.chiefdelphi.com/bovlb/{size}/167232_2.png","created_at":"2024-09-01T21:02:20.949Z","cooked":"<aside class="quote no-group" data-username="narmstro" data-post="1" data-topic="470539">
<div class="title">
<div class="quote-controls"></div>
<img loading="lazy" alt="" width="24" height="24" src="https://www.chiefdelphi.com/letter_avatar_proxy/v4/letter/n/5e9695/48.png" class="avatar"> narmstro:</div>
<blockquote>
<p><em>Side Note</em>: I know feature creep is always an issue, but could WPILib benefit from integrating <span class="abbreviation">PID<template class="tooltiptext" data-text="Proportional Integral Derivative"></template></span> and the 3 feedforward classes into some form of ClosedLoop class/interface setup that makes the implementation of control loop schemes more ergonomic.</p>
</blockquote>
</aside>
<p>I’d like to see that too.  WPILIB now has at least six different feed forward classes<sup class="footnote-ref"><a href="#footnote-3420009-1" id="footnote-ref-3420009-1">[1]</a></sup>, nine feedback controllers<sup class="footnote-ref"><a href="#footnote-3420009-2" id="footnote-ref-3420009-2">[2]</a></sup>, five limiters and other filters<sup class="footnote-ref"><a href="#footnote-3420009-3" id="footnote-ref-3420009-3">[3]</a></sup>, five or six derived commands<sup class="footnote-ref"><a href="#footnote-3420009-4" id="footnote-ref-3420009-4">[4]</a></sup>, and two or three derived subsystems<sup class="footnote-ref"><a href="#footnote-3420009-5" id="footnote-ref-3420009-5">[5]</a></sup>.  There’s considerable variety in how they are created and invoked.  If I were doing it over from scratch, I think I’d be tempted to build it by writing factories that construct suppliers and then chaining them together.</p>
<hr class="footnotes-sep">

<ol class="footnotes-list">
<li id="footnote-3420009-1" class="footnote-item"><p><a href="https://github.wpilib.org/allwpilib/docs/release/java/edu/wpi/first/math/controller/ArmFeedforward.html" rel="noopener nofollow ugc">ArmFeedforward</a>, <a href="https://github.wpilib.org/allwpilib/docs/release/java/edu/wpi/first/math/controller/ControlAffinePlantInversionFeedforward.html" rel="noopener nofollow ugc">ControlAffinePlantInversionFeedforward</a>, <a href="https://github.wpilib.org/allwpilib/docs/release/java/edu/wpi/first/math/controller/DifferentialDriveFeedforward.html" rel="noopener nofollow ugc">DifferentialDriveFeedforward</a>, <a href="https://github.wpilib.org/allwpilib/docs/release/java/edu/wpi/first/math/controller/ElevatorFeedforward.html" rel="noopener nofollow ugc">ElevatorFeedforward</a>, <a href="https://github.wpilib.org/allwpilib/docs/release/java/edu/wpi/first/math/controller/LinearPlantInversionFeedforward.html" rel="noopener nofollow ugc">LinearPlantInversionFeedforward</a>, <a href="https://github.wpilib.org/allwpilib/docs/release/java/edu/wpi/first/math/controller/SimpleMotorFeedforward.html" rel="noopener nofollow ugc">SimpleMotorFeedforward</a> <a href="#footnote-ref-3420009-1" class="footnote-backref">↩︎</a></p>
</li>
<li id="footnote-3420009-2" class="footnote-item"><p><a href="https://github.wpilib.org/allwpilib/docs/release/java/edu/wpi/first/math/controller/BangBangController.html" rel="noopener nofollow ugc">BangBangController</a>, <a href="https://github.wpilib.org/allwpilib/docs/release/java/edu/wpi/first/math/controller/HolonomicDriveController.html" rel="noopener nofollow ugc">HolonomicDriveController</a>, <a href="https://github.wpilib.org/allwpilib/docs/release/java/edu/wpi/first/math/controller/ImplicitModelFollower.html" rel="noopener nofollow ugc">ImplicitModelFollower</a>, <a href="https://github.wpilib.org/allwpilib/docs/release/java/edu/wpi/first/math/controller/LinearQuadraticRegulator.html" rel="noopener nofollow ugc">LinearQuadraticRegulator</a>, <a href="https://github.wpilib.org/allwpilib/docs/release/java/edu/wpi/first/math/controller/LTVDifferentialDriveController.html" rel="noopener nofollow ugc">LTVDifferentialDriveController</a>, <a href="https://github.wpilib.org/allwpilib/docs/release/java/edu/wpi/first/math/controller/LTVUnicycleController.html" rel="noopener nofollow ugc">LTVUnicycleController</a>, <a href="https://github.wpilib.org/allwpilib/docs/release/java/edu/wpi/first/math/controller/PIDController.html" rel="noopener nofollow ugc">PIDController</a>, <a href="https://github.wpilib.org/allwpilib/docs/release/java/edu/wpi/first/math/controller/ProfiledPIDController.html" rel="noopener nofollow ugc">ProfiledPIDController</a>, <a href="https://github.wpilib.org/allwpilib/docs/release/java/edu/wpi/first/math/controller/RamseteController.html" rel="noopener nofollow ugc">RamseteController</a> <a href="#footnote-ref-3420009-2" class="footnote-backref">↩︎</a></p>
</li>
